HEADWORD: Glyconic
<hw>Gly*con"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ a kind of
verse, so called from its inventor, <ets>Glycon</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Pros.)</fld> <def>Consisting of a spondee, a choriamb, and a
pyrrhic; -- applied to a kind of verse in Greek and Latin poetry.</def>
-- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Pros.)</fld> <def>A glyconic
verse.</def></def2>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

